questiontext.text:
Determine whether descriptive or inferential statistics was used:

A study conducted by D.A.R.E. found that people who smoke at least one pack of cigarettes per day have lower life expectancies than those who don't.
Which of the following is a qualitative variable?

answer.text: Height of a roller coaster
Time taken to run a mile

questiontext.text:
State the level of measurement used to measure the following variable:

Grades earned on this exam: A, B, C, D, F
Which of the following is an example of a cluster sample?

answer.text: In a school district with 7 middle schools, all 8th graders at 3 of the schools are surveyed about how often they eat school lunch.
Every 50th bottle of soda on the assembly line is taken aside and weighed to make sure that the amount of soda in a bottle is consistent.
Prior to a state election, 100 likely voters in each county are asked how they will vote on an amendment to the state constitution.
Using a random number generator, a researcher selects 1000 people to ask their favorite color.

questiontext.text: Which of the following states that subjects will change their behavior if they know that they are participating in an experiment?
Which of the following is a graph that represents the cumulative frequencies for the classes in a frequency distribution?
Which of the following data sets contains an outlier?
Which of the following events are independent?

answer.text: A father being left-handed and his child being left-handed
Having a large head and wearing a large hat
Getting a raise and purchasing a new car
Liking the color red and liking spaghetti

questiontext.text: Which of the following is not a requirement for a valid probability distribution?

answer.text: \( P(x) \geq 0 \) for all \( x \)
\( P(x) \leq 1 \) for all \( x \)
\( P(x) = 0 \) for at least one \( x \)

questiontext.text: Which of the following is not a property of a good estimator.
In which case is a Type II error committed?

answer.text:
Test Value: 1.83

Critical Value: 1.96

Decision: Do not reject H_0.

Test Value: 2.34

Critical Values: +/- 2.16

Decision: Do not reject H_0.

Test Value: -1.61

Critical Value: +/- 1.96

Decision: Reject H_0.

Test Value: -2.65

Critical Value: -1.72

Decision: Reject H_0.

questiontext.text:
Compute the midpoint of the following class:

10-20

Round to the nearest tenth, if necessary.

You have gathered data on your classmates' favorite flavors of ice cream, and would like to make a pie chart with your findings. Compute the size (in degrees) of the wedge corresponding to chocolate. Round your answer to the nearest tenth of a degree, if necessary.


Flavor Frequency
Vanilla 12
Chocolate 19
Mint
 9
Peanut Butter
 10

Of the 25 brightest stars, the distances from Earth (in light-years) for those with distances less than 100 light years are found below. Find the mean for the data.

Round your answer to the nearest tenth of a light year, if necessary.

The data show the maximum wind speeds for a sample of 40 states. Find the mean for the data.

Round your answer to the nearest tenth of a mile per hour, if necessary.

Find the median of the following data set. Round your answer to the nearest tenth, if necessary.

83   108   65   89   80   74   102   90
The data show the traveler spending in billions of dollars for a recent year for a sample of the states. Find the range for the data. Round your answer to the nearest tenth, if necessary.
The number of annual precipitation days for one-half of the 50 largest U.S. cities is listed below. Find the (sample) variance of the data. Round your answer to the nearest hundredth, if necessary.
The frequency distribution shows a sample of the waterfall heights, in feet, of 28 waterfalls. Find the standard deviation for the data. Round your answer to the nearest hundredth, if necessary.
The data show the population (in thousands) for a recent year of a sample of cities in South Carolina. Find the percentile rank of 37. Round to the nearest whole number.

Find the interquartile range of the following data set. Round your answer to the nearest tenth, if necessary.

239, 266, 245, 236, 241, 246, 240, 249, 251, 238, 228, 248, 232
A single card is selected at random from an ordinary deck of cards. Find the probability that the card is a black face card. Round your answer to three decimal places.
A fair 20-sided die is rolled. Find the probability that the die does not land on a number that is a perfect square. Round your answer to three decimal places.

The following table shows the blood types of a random sample of 50 people.


Find the probability that a randomly selected person from the sample has either type B blood or type O blood. Round your answer to three decimal places.

According to the Bureau of the Census, the following statistics describe the number (in thousands) of young adults living at home or in a dormitory in the year 2004.


Choose one student at random. Find the probability that the student is female or aged 25-34. Round your answer to three decimal places.
Two cards are drawn from an ordinary deck with replacement. Find the probability that both are clubs. Round your answer to three decimal places.

Smart TV's have seen success in the United States market. During the 2nd quarter of 2017, 61% of TVs sold in the United States were smart TV's. Choose four households and find the probability that at least one of the 4 households had a Smart TV. Round your answer to three decimal places.
How many permutations of the letters can be made from the word CLINICIAN?
How many ways can 3 sopranos and 5 altos be selected from 7 sopranos and 9 altos? Hint: The order in which singers are selected does not matter.
Find the mean of the probability distribution below. Round your answer to the nearest tenth, if necessary.

A producer plans an outdoor regatta for May 13. The cost of the regatta is $7500. This includes advertising, security, printing tickets, entertainment, etc. The producer anticipates making $16,000 in profit (i.e. after expenses) if all goes well. But if it rains, the regatta will have to be canceled. The weatherman says there is a 25% chance of rain on May 13. Find the producer's expected profit.
Two dice are rolled. Find the standard deviation of the sum of the two dice. Round your answer to the nearest tenth.

It is estimated that 40% of all commuters ride to work in carpools. If 8 workers are randomly selected, find the probability that exactly 6 of them ride to work in carpools. Round your answer to three decimal places.
If 60% of all women are employed outside the home, find the probability that over half of a sample of 10 women is employed outside the home. Round your answer to three decimal places.
Find the area under the standard normal curve to the right of \( z = -1.18 \). Round your answer to four decimal places.
Use the standard normal distribution to find \( P(0.41 < z < 0.73) \).
Find the \( z \) value such that 96.71% of the area under the standard normal curve is to the left of it. Round your answer to two decimal places.

The mean temperature for Cleveland in September is \( 74^\circ \), with a standard deviation of \( 3^\circ \). If I attend the Cleveland Browns' first home game (it'll be in September), then what is the probability that the temperature is higher than 80 degrees? Round your answer to four decimal places, and assume the variable is normally distributed.

On the daily run of an express bus, the average number of passengers is 48. The standard deviation is 4. Assume the variable is normally distributed. Find the probability that the bus will have between 39 and 43 passengers. Round your answer to four decimal places.

The average thickness of books on a library shelf is 8.3 centimeters. The standard deviation is 0.6 centimeter. If 20% of the books are undersized, find the maximum thickness of the undersized books on the library shelf. Round your answer to three decimal places, and assume the variable is normally distributed.

Procter and Gamble reported that an American family of four washes an average of 2000 pounds of clothes each year. If the standard deviation of the distribution is 187.5 pounds, find the probability that the mean of a randomly selected sample of 50 families of 4 will be less than 1950 pounds. Round your answer to four decimal places, and assume the variable is normally distributed.
Find \( z_{\alpha / 2} \) for a 99% confidence interval.

A random sample of 36 drivers used on average 749 gallons of gasoline per year. If the standard deviation of the population is 32 gallons, find the lower bound for a 90% confidence interval of the mean for all drivers. Round your answer to the nearest tenth.

How large a sample is needed to estimate the population mean for the amount of money a person spends on Christmas presents within $1 and be 95% confident? The standard deviation of the population is $6.50.

A random sample of 18 physicians in a large hospital showed that they worked on average 43.4 hours per week. The standard deviation of the sample was 2.8. Find the upper bound of a 90% confidence interval for the mean. Round your answer to the nearest tenth of an hour.

Research by Steelcase found the average worker gets interrupted every 11 minutes and takes 23 minutes to get back on task. From a random sample of 200 workers, 168 said they are interrupted every 11 minutes. Find the lower bound of the 99% confidence interval of the population proportion of workers who are interrupted every 11 minutes. Round your answer to three decimal places.

A researcher wishes to see if the average number of sick days a worker takes per year is greater than 5. A random sample of 32 workers at a large department store had a mean of 5.6. The standard deviation of the population is 1.2. Find the test value. Round your answer to two decimal places.

The director of a medical hospital feels that her surgeons perform fewer operations per year than the national average of 211. She selected a random sample of 15 surgeons and found that the mean number of operations they performed was 208.8. The standard deviation of the sample was 3.8. Find the critical value if \( \alpha = 0.01 \).

An automobile owner found that 20 years ago, 76% of Americans said that they would prefer to purchase an American automobile. He believes that number has changed since then. He selected a random sample of 56 Americans and 38 said that they would prefer an American automobile. Find the P-value. Round your answer to four decimal places.

On a scale of 0-10 (0 = extremely easy, 5 = medium, 10 = extremely hard), how difficult would you say this test was? (All answers in the 0-10 range will be marked correct; any answer that is negative or higher than 10 will be marked incorrect.)
